Below is an example of C# code for implementing rigid body physics in a 3D environment using Unity game engine:

```csharp
using UnityEngine;

public class RigidBodyPhysics : MonoBehaviour
{
    private Rigidbody rb;

    // Variables for applying forces
    public float forceMultiplier = 10f;
    public float torqueMultiplier = 5f;

    // Start is called before the first frame update
    void Start()
    {
        rb = GetComponent<Rigidbody>();
    }

    // Update is called once per frame
    void Update()
    {
        // Applying force
        float moveHorizontal = Input.GetAxis("Horizontal");
        float moveVertical = Input.GetAxis("Vertical");

        Vector3 force = new Vector3(moveHorizontal, 0.0f, moveVertical) * forceMultiplier;
        rb.AddForce(force);

        // Applying torque
        float rotateX = Input.GetAxis("Mouse X");
        float rotateY = Input.GetAxis("Mouse Y");

        Vector3 torque = new Vector3(rotateY, rotateX, 0.0f) * torqueMultiplier;
        rb.AddTorque(torque);
    }
}
```

This script attaches to a game object in Unity that has a Rigidbody component. It allows the object to be controlled by applying forces and torques.

The `Start` method initializes the `Rigidbody` component of the object.

The `Update` method is called every frame. It reads input from the keyboard or mouse to determine the force and torque to be applied to the object. 
- The `Input.GetAxis` method reads horizontal and vertical inputs for movement.
- The forces are calculated by multiplying the inputs by the `forceMultiplier` variable.
- The `AddForce` method adds the force to the Rigidbody.
- The `Input.GetAxis` method reads mouse inputs for rotation.
- The torques are calculated by multiplying the inputs by the `torqueMultiplier` variable.
- The `AddTorque` method adds the torque to the Rigidbody.

You can customize the `forceMultiplier` and `torqueMultiplier` variables to control the intensity of the forces and torques applied to the object.

Remember to attach this script to a game object with a `Rigidbody` component in your Unity project for it to work as intended.
